SCRAPIE - JAPAN
***************
A ProMED post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>
Date: 25 Oct, 1999
From: ProMED <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: OIE Reporting

Emergency report
Text of a fax received on 6 October 1999 from Dr Kenichi Matsubara,
Director of Animal Health
Division, Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries, Tokyo:
Report date: 6 October 1999.
Nature of diagnosis: clinical and laboratory.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 30 September 1999.
Estimated date of first infection: unknown.
Outbreaks:
Location: Nishi-Tama, Tokyo prefecture
No. of outbreaks: 1
Description of affected population: one sheep in a flock used for
educational purposes at a nursing school.
Total number of animals in the outbreak:
species: ovi
susceptible: 13
cases: 1
deaths:0
destroyed:1
slaughtered:0
Diagnosis: the affected sheep was killed for diagnostic purposes.
A. Laboratory where diagnosis was made: National Institute of Animal
Health, Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries.
B. Diagnostic tests used: pathological and immunopathological test of the
brain.
Epidemiology:
A. Source of agent / origin of infection: under investigation.
B. Mode of spread: the parents of the affected sheep are suspected to have
been introduced from a farm where scrapie occurred 15 years ago.
C. Other epidemiological details: the rest of the sheep in the flock show
no clinical signs of scrapie. They have been isolated and are under
observation.
Control measures during reporting period:
- disinfection of the facilities;
- isolation of the sheep in the affected and neighbouring premises;
- nine epidemiologically related sheep in neighbouring premises were
destroyed.
--
ProMED
e-mail: promed@promedmail.org
